Session 1: Enter the Matrix with Coding¶

In this notebook, we will see how to perform matrix arithmetic on a matrix and then see it in the context of computer graphics.

# Import numpy library
import numpy as np

Simple matrix arithmetic¶

In [2]:
# Create my matrices from the homework
x = np.array([[-1,0,3],[2,-4, 1],[ 3,4,-2]])
y = np.array([[ 2,1,0],[0,-2,-4],[-1,3,8]])
print('x = \n',x)
print('y = \n',y)

x = 
 [[-1  0  3]
 [ 2 -4  1]
 [ 3  4 -2]]
y = 
 [[ 2  1  0]
 [ 0 -2 -4]
 [-1  3  8]]
In [3]:
# Matrix addition
sumMatrix = x+y
print('x+y =\n',sumMatrix)

x+y =
 [[ 1  1  3]
 [ 2 -6 -3]
 [ 2  7  6]]
In [4]:
# Matrix multiply. Notice this is @ and not *
multMatrix = x@y
print('x*y = \n',multMatrix)

# Element-wise multiplication
multElementsMatrix = x*y
print('x*y (element by element) = \n',multElementsMatrix)

x*y = 
 [[ -5   8  24]
 [  3  13  24]
 [  8 -11 -32]]
x*y (element by element) = 
 [[ -2   0   0]
 [  0   8  -4]
 [ -3  12 -16]]

In [11]:
# Convert the image to a matrix
imageArray = np.asarray(imgGray)
# Lighten the image
alteredImage = imageArray+20
# Convert back to an image 
img2 = Image.fromarray(alteredImage)
# Display the new image 
display(img2)

Invert an image¶

In [12]:
# Invert the image
alteredImage = 255 - imageArray
# Convert back to an image 
img2 = Image.fromarray(alteredImage)
# Display the new image 
display(img2)
In [13]:
# For fun let's play with this idea a bit. 
alteredImage = np.copy(imageArray)
borderSize = 30
alteredImage[borderSize:-borderSize,borderSize:-borderSize] = 255 - alteredImage[borderSize:-borderSize,borderSize:-borderSize]
# Convert back to an image 
img2 = Image.fromarray(alteredImage)
display(img2)

width, height = img.size
width, height
Out[16]:
(300, 407)
In [17]:
submatrixSize = 75
In [18]:
numberOfSwappedSubmatrices = 20
In [19]:
alteredImage = np.copy(imageArray)
for _ in range(numberOfSwappedSubmatrices):
    rowIndex = randint(0, height-submatrixSize-1)
    colIndex = randint(0, width-submatrixSize-1)
    alteredImage[rowIndex:rowIndex+submatrixSize,colIndex:colIndex+submatrixSize] = 255 - alteredImage[rowIndex:rowIndex+submatrixSize,colIndex:colIndex+submatrixSize]
# Convert back to an image 
img2 = Image.fromarray(alteredImage)
display(img2)

Further tips¶

In [20]:
# How do you delete a row? 
print('Before delete: x = \n',x)
xDelete = np.delete(x,1,0)
print('After delete: x = \n',x)
print('deleted matrix = \n',xDelete)

Before delete: x = 
 [[-1  0  3]
 [ 2 -4  1]
 [ 3  4 -2]]
After delete: x = 
 [[-1  0  3]
 [ 2 -4  1]
 [ 3  4 -2]]
deleted matrix = 
 [[-1  0  3]
 [ 3  4 -2]]
